# What Gets Ignored (NOT pushed to GitHub)

## ‚úÖ IGNORED - Safe from Git:

### Environment Files (SENSITIVE!)
- .env.local              # Your Supabase credentials
- .env                    # Any other env file
- .env*.local             # All local environment variants

### Database Files
- db.json                 # Old JSON database
- db.json.backup          # Backup of old DB
- lib/db.ts.backup        # Backup of old DB handler
- *.backup                # Any backup files

### Build & Dependencies
- node_modules/           # NPM packages
- .next/                  # Next.js build output
- dist/                   # Distribution builds
- *.tsbuildinfo          # TypeScript build info

### IDE & OS
- .DS_Store              # macOS Finder metadata
- .vscode/*              # VS Code settings (except extensions.json)
- .idea                  # JetBrains IDEs
- *.swp, *.swo           # Vim swap files
- Thumbs.db              # Windows thumbnails

### Logs
- *.log                  # All log files
- npm-debug.log*
- yarn-debug.log*

---

## üì§ TRACKED - Will be pushed to GitHub:

### Source Code
- app/                   # All application code
- components/            # React components
- lib/prisma.ts         # Prisma client (safe to share)
- prisma/schema.prisma  # Database schema (safe to share)

### Configuration (Safe)
- .env.example          # Template WITHOUT real credentials
- package.json          # Dependencies list
- tsconfig.json         # TypeScript config
- next.config.ts        # Next.js config
- tailwind.config.ts    # Tailwind config

### Documentation
- README.md
- SUPABASE_SETUP.md
- .gitignore.info       # This file!

---

## üîí Security Notes:

1. **.env.local** contains your REAL database password - NEVER commit this!
2. **.env.example** is safe - it has placeholders, not real credentials
3. **db.json** is ignored - even though old, better safe than sorry
4. **Backup files** (.backup) are all ignored automatically

---

## üß™ To Verify:

Run: `git status`

If you see:
- ‚ùå .env.local listed ‚Üí STOP! Remove it: `git reset .env.local`
- ‚úÖ .env.example listed ‚Üí Good! This is the template

If you accidentally committed .env.local:
```bash
git rm --cached .env.local
git commit -m "Remove sensitive env file"
```
